CC91B2EBA2DD43F795C3DFE20B3EF879.description:
Express the relationship among pressure, volume, temperature, and the number of
moles of a gas quantitatively, conceptually, and graphically.

F0398C394D064FE982DD58287A39A42A.description:
Qualitatively and quantitatively relate changes in the temperature and pressure of a gas
to particle motion and number of collisions.

EC175AA750A049778611563DF2E8D5C5.description:
Plan and carry out investigations to determine how the atomic and molecular motion in
chemical and physical processes is related to the kinetic molecular theory.

2F480CBAC63543858EAA96C13054550C.description:
Plan and carry out a strong acid-strong base titration to determine the concentration of
an unknown acidic or basic solution.

95ECD6AB622B47F7BECAA893D1066A72.description:
Use multiple models to predict the relative properties of strong, weak, concentrated, and
dilute acids and bases.

9F59AB95CCB84B729A6B35827F57034D.description:
Use the periodic table and computational thinking to derive chemical formulas and
names of acids and bases.

CEE712AE62864E7E92BAC82B2C667974.description:
Obtain, evaluate, and communicate information concerning the properties of acids and
bases.

92F4940FFA494FE488112BCC04DC66B3.description:
Make qualitative and quantitative claims, based on ion concentration, about the acidic, basic, or
neutral characteristics of a solution.

EEC6C666C9174F629CFE061CC0AF02A4.description:
Design and conduct experiments to evaluate the effect of solute concentration on the
colligative properties of a solution.

D5458619C34647858BDD1DFDBF7EC3D8.description:
Analyze and interpret data to explain the effects of temperature on the solubility of
solid, liquid, and gaseous solutes in a solvent and the effects of pressure on the
solubility of gaseous solutes.

0AE41C6848E541679E63DE60F9CFF8CD.description:
Use mathematics and computational thinking to prepare solutions from both solids and
concentrated solutions when given a desired molarity and volume.

9D86AB9D5B604CB887A16644D33B42CE.description: Develop and use models to illustrate solute-solvent interactions.

07A1EFF9230843178A571109193D17CF.description:
Use mathematics and computational thinking to express the concentrations of given
solutions in terms of molarity and molality.

DEAD1D95EEB141379D86F7C71879EE25.description:
Obtain, evaluate, and communicate information concerning factors that affect solubility and the
properties of solutions.

BB3C9009404347BAAD45616B3CC8E2DF.description:
Use mathematics and computational thinking to perform gas stoichiometry calculations
involving mass, volume, and number of moles at standard temperature and pressure
(STP).

13D4510EE13A4953ADA9B1A597CA8F28.description:
Qualitatively and quantitatively determine the limiting reactant when given the masses
of all reactants.

F68CF0CB1A1D48899B6F502CC266AA3F.description:
Use mathematical models to reveal the relationships among the theoretical, actual, and
percent yields of chemical reactions.

210F7BD225DB4228A4E4DDE1165C0E1D.description:
Use mathematical representations of the mole concept to solve reaction stoichiometry
problems, involving mole-to-mole conversions, mass-to-mole conversions, and
mass-to-mass conversions.

7AD0DB15EE0943AF8C4340D68300A1E3.description:
Quantitatively apply the concepts of the mole and Avogadro’s number to conceptualize
and calculate percent composition and empirical or molecular formulas of common
compounds.

95D63B7DFF534A18B70E99AF7BA12CEB.description:
Use stoichiometric ratios to support the claim that atoms, and therefore mass, are conserved
during chemical reactions.

67C97A2858B845DAB9DB9722966B57A7.description:
Construct an explanation, using particle diagrams and collision theory, for how particle
size, concentration, and temperature affect the rate of a chemical reaction.

D88C010AAC4742A28E88FA507789846F.description:
Analyze and interpret temperature and bond energy data to classify a reaction as
endothermic or exothermic.

7426733C5FC24EA886C5E9E77F13379A.description:
Use qualitative and quantitative reasoning to classify chemical reactions, predict the
products of single replacement and double replacement reactions, and represent
chemical reactions using ionic equations.

40556CE091AD4849B369BFB81108F02A.description:
Use qualitative and quantitative reasoning to describe and balance chemical equations
to satisfy the law of conservation of matter.

CB733662D4574414B81EC8DD4C7402FA.description: Develop and use multiple types of models to represent chemical reactions.

652343AAB8EE4408AF346647DB3FE176.description:
Analyze and interpret data to compare the strengths of intermolecular forces and to
explain how these forces affect physical properties.

E6B55D9ABEB0499D8312FB1703D81A1D.description:
Analyze and interpret data from the periodic table to derive chemical formulas and
names for ionic and covalent compounds.

FE46405914E54C2B89FF02B29E15A688.description:
Construct an explanation of the polarity of a molecule based on electronegativity data
and molecular geometry.

0840353D3E8C42B5B69B6ED708C4C7D7.description:
Develop and use models based on valence shell electron pair repulsion (VSEPR) theory
to predict the shape of a molecule up to four electron domains around the central atom.

F4FE3AB1FE8F4D36B719A3574C19D6C4.description:
Plan and carry out an investigation to identify specific physical and chemical properties
of compounds formed from ionic, covalent, and metallic bonding.

265857ABB39B4DD9B84CDE70070E158C.description:
Construct an explanation of the change in potential energy that occurs when chemical
bonds are formed.

5673531CD6484167A1040562E891C3C6.description:
Develop and use Lewis dot diagrams to model the formation of covalent and ionic
bonds.

1A348476E6F04A64843406ED22A06C62.description:
Construct explanations of the formation of intramolecular and intermolecular forces and their
effects on atomic and molecular interactions.

1894066A7B7B4844A73786BE939B7FB4.description: Motion and Stability: Forces and Interactions

06900D146FED4C47B2E81486C9631F9E.description:
Construct explanations of how periodic trends can be used to predict the properties of
elements.

2E0D95FADC114C178E05BD821538984D.description:
Ask questions to determine the relationship between an element’s physical and chemical
properties and its position on the periodic table.

3DD522F7ED324AD1A54CB355CD832FC7.description:
Analyze and interpret data to identify or describe an element based on its number of
protons, its relative abundance of isotopes, its organization and placement of electrons,
and its light emission spectrum.

C721687C940743FCAE0ECC2119F85098.description:
Develop and use models of an element’s subatomic particles to compare and contrast its
atoms, ions, and isotopes.

91AA08B633134CACB04E142487C8D242.description:
Assess the merits and limitations of historic and modern atomic models pertaining to
the presence, position, mass, and charge of subatomic particles.

9F2ABFB9277F4420A79A7BB9AF76A574.description: Use the periodic table as a model to predict the structure and properties of atoms and elements.
